Section III&hyph;D&hyph;2&hyph;b&hyph;(5). Experiments with recombinant DNA-modified arthropods or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
small animals associated with plants, or with arthropods or small animals with 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
recombinant DNA-modified microorganisms associated with them if the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
recombinant DNA-modified microorganisms have no recognized potential for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
serious detrimental impact on managed or natural ecosystems (see Section V&hyph;W). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=81 g=1 f=1 -->
Section III&hyph;E. Exempt Experiments 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The following recombinant DNA molecules are exempt from the NIH Guidelines 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and registration with the Institutional Biosafety Committee is not required: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Section III&hyph;E&hyph;1. Those that are not in organisms or viruses. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Section III&hyph;E&hyph;2. Those that consist entirely of DNA segments from a single 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
nonchromosomal or viral DNA source, though one or more of the segments may be 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
a synthetic equivalent. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Section III&hyph;E&hyph;3. Those that consist entirely of DNA from a prokaryotic host 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
including its indigenous plasmids or viruses when propagated only in that host (or a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
closely related strain of the same species), or when transferred to another host by 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
well established physiological means. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Section III&hyph;E&hyph;4. Those that consist entirely of DNA from an eukaryotic host 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
including its chloroplasts, mitochondria, or plasmids (but excluding viruses) when 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
propagated only in that host (or a closely related strain of the same species). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Section III&hyph;E&hyph;5. Those that consist entirely of DNA segments from different species 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that exchange DNA by known physiological processes, though one or more of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
segments may be a synthetic equivalent. A list of such exchangers will be prepared 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and periodically revised by the NIH Director with advice of the RAC after 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
appropriate notice and opportunity for public comment (see Section 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
IV&hyph;C&hyph;1&hyph;b&hyph;(1)&hyph;(c)). See Appendices A&hyph;I through A&hyph;VI for a list of natural
exchangers 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that are exempt from the NIH Guidelines. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Section III&hyph;E&hyph;6. Those that do not present a significant risk to health or the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
environment (see Section IV&hyph;C&hyph;1&hyph;b&hyph;(1)&hyph;(c)), as determined by the NIH Director, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
with the advice of the RAC, and following appropriate notice and opportunity for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
public comment. See Appendix C for other classes of experiments which are 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
exempt from the NIH Guidelines. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
Section IV, Roles and Responsibilities 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=81 g=1 f=1 -->
Section IV&hyph;A. Policy 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The safe conduct of experiments involving recombinant DNA depends on the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
individual conducting such activities. The NIH Guidelines cannot anticipate every 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
possible situation. Motivation and good judgment are the key essentials to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
protection of health and the environment. The NIH Guidelines are intended to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
assist the institution, Institutional Biosafety Committee, Biological Safety Officer, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and Principal Investigator in determining safeguards that should be implemented. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The NIH Guidelines will never be complete or final since all conceivable 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
experiments involving recombinant DNA cannot be foreseen. Therefore, it is the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
responsibility of the institution and those associated with it to adhere to the intent of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
NIH Guidelines as well as to their specifics. Each institution (and the Institutional 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Biosafety Committee acting on its behalf) is responsible for ensuring that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
recombinant DNA activities comply with the NIH Guidelines. General recognition 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of institutional authority and responsibility properly establishes accountability for 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
safe conduct of the research at the local level. The following roles and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
responsibilities constitute an administrative framework in which safety is an essential 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and integral part of research involving recombinant DNA molecules. Further 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
clarifications and interpretations of roles and responsibilities will be issued by the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
NIH as necessary. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

